{{spanish name 2|Salas|Vargas}} {{Infobox military person | name = Benito Salas Vargas | image = | caption = | birth_date = April 1770 | death_date = {{Death date | 1816 | 09 | 18 | df=yes }}<ref name="lanacion">[http://www.lanacion.com.co/2010/07/17/huellas-de-la-independencia-en-el-huila/ Huellas de la Independencia en el Huila] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110417/http://www.lanacion.com.co/2010/07/17/huellas-de-la-independencia-en-el-huila/ |date=September 27, 2011 }}</ref> | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial = | birth_place = | death_place = [[Neiva, Colombia]] | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | nickname = | birth_name = | allegiance = [[Patriot (Spanish American Revolution)|Spanish American Patriots]] | branch = | serviceyears = | rank = [[Colonel]] | servicenumber = | unit = | commands = | battles = [[Spanish reconquest of New Granada]] | battles_label = | awards = | relations = | laterwork = }}
'''Benito Salas Vargas''' (1770 – 18 September 1816) was a military and social leader during [[Colombia]]'s (then known as [[United Provinces of New Granada|New Granada]]) independence war (1810–1819). He fought against [[Pablo Morillo]] during the [[Spanish reconquest of New Granada]]. In 1811 he joined the forces of [[Brigadier]] Jose Diaz,<ref name="lanacion" /> as part of the army of the United Provinces of New Granada commanded by General Antonio Baraya.<ref name="lanacion" /> On December 8, 1812, in [[Timaná]], he swore recognition to the Congress of the United Provinces.<ref name="lanacion" /> He fought with the troops of [[Antonio Nariño]].<ref name="lanacion" /> On 29 June 1816, he fought in the battle of Cuchilla del Tambo<ref name="lanacion" /> where the [[Patriot (Spanish American Revolution)|patriot troops]] were defeated by the royalists commanded by [[Juan José de Sámano y Uribarri]]. On July 10, 1816, '''Salas''' was captured.<ref name="lanacion" />
In September 1816, by order of the [[Purificación, Tolima|Purificación]] Tribunal,<ref name="lanacion" /> Salas was executed<ref name="Crónicas de Bogotá, CAPITULO XLVI ">Pedro M. Ibáñez http://www.banrepcultural.org/blaavirtual/historia/cronic/cap46.htm</ref> in [[Neiva, Colombia|Neiva]]'s main square, where his hands and head were exhibited. His head was buried in the terrain which would later become ''La Manguita'' [[Hacienda]]. In 1936, the Colombian government inaugurated Neiva's airport in the hacienda, and renamed it in 1986 as the [[Benito Salas Airport]] in honour of Salas.<ref name="lanacion" />
