{{notability|Biographies|date=January 2017}} [[File:Marsha Coleman-Adebayo.jpg|thumb|Marsha Coleman-Adebayo]] '''Marsha Coleman-Adebayo''' is an American former senior policy analyst for the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA). Beginning in 1996, she filed complaints alleging that a company from the United States was mining [[vanadium]] in South Africa and harming the environment and human health. The EPA did not respond, and Coleman-Adebayo reported her concerns to other organizations. When the EPA subsequently did not promote Coleman-Adebayo at her request, she filed suit against the agency, alleging racial and gender discrimination. On August 18, 2000, a federal jury found EPA guilty of violating the civil rights of Coleman-Adebayo on the basis of race, sex, color and a [[hostile work environment]], under the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref name="post"/> Her experience inspired passage of the Notification and Federal Employee Anti-discrimination and Retaliation Act of 2002 ([[No FEAR Act]]).
During the legal proceedings, Coleman-Adebayo remained employed at the EPA. When she was diagnosed with hypertension, the agency agreed to let her work from home. After five years of [[telecommuting]] and another lawsuit, the EPA ordered Coleman-Adebayo to return to the office, placing her on unpaid leave when she did not comply.<ref name="post">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/09/AR2006070900741_pf.html Fears, D., "Coming Soon: A Tale of Whistleblowing at the EPA"], [[Washington Post]], 10 July 2006</ref>
Coleman-Adebayo is a founder and leader of the No FEAR Coalition<ref name="post"/> and EPA Employees Against Racial Discrimination.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} Through her leadership the No FEAR Coalition, working closely with Representative [[James Sensenbrenner]], organized a successful grass-roots campaign and secured passage of the "[[No-FEAR Act|Notification of Federal Employees Anti-discrimination and Retaliation Act]]," the first Civil Rights Law of the 21st Century. The Act was signed into law by President [[George W. Bush]] in 2002.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}
Coleman-Adebayo currently serves on the Board of Directors of the [[National Whistleblower Center]], a nonpartisan, nonprofit, advocacy group dedicated to protecting the rights of employee whistleblowers.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} ''Good Housekeeping'' presented her with its Women in Government award in 2003.<ref name="post"/> Her first book, "No Fear: A Whistleblower's Triumph Over Corruption and Retaliation at the EPA" was published in September 2011 by Lawrence Hill Books.
As of April 2015, she also serves on the Green [[Shadow Cabinet]] of the United States as "Director of Governmental Transparency and Accountability".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenshadowcabinet.us/members|title=Green Shadow Cabinet Members|accessdate=2015-04-07|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330010626/http://greenshadowcabinet.us/members|archivedate=2015-03-30|df=}}</ref>
In June 2015, Coleman-Adebayo endorsed [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] presidential candidate Dr. [[Jill Stein]] while speaking at the [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name="Bernd">{{cite news|url=http://www.truth-out.org/news/item/31570-we-re-in-an-age-of-the-statistically-unlikely-green-party-candidate-jill-stein-announces-presidential-run|title="An Age of the Statistically Unlikely": An Interview With Presidential Candidate Jill Stein|last=Bernd|first=Candice|publisher=[[TruthOut]]|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref>
==External links== *[http://www.marshacoleman-adebayo.com Marsha Coleman-Adebayo's web site] *[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927131128/http://www.nofearcoalition.org/index.html No FEAR Coalition web site] *[https://web.archive.org/web/20070811225355/http://www.pogo.org/halloffame/ Dr. Coleman-Adebayo's induction into the Project on Government Oversight Hall of Fame] *[http://alum.barnard.edu/site/PageServer?pagename=alu_act_0602coleman_adebayo Dr. Coleman-Adebayo bio from Barnard College] *[http://www.whistleblowers.org/html/press_2006.html Announcement of Dr. Coleman-Adebayo defense fund] *[http://www.whistleblowers.org|National Whistleblower Center]
