{{fieldhockey-bio-stub}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}
{{Use Irish English|date=February 2015}}
'''Seamus Daly''' ([[Irish language|Irish]]: ''' Séamus Ó Dálaigh''') is an [[Irish republican]] from [[Kilmurray]], [[Castleblayney]], [[County Monaghan]]. He was [[Indictment|charged]] with  being a member of the [[Real Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) in Dublin's [[Special Criminal Court]] in 2004, pleaded guilty and was sentenced to three and half years in prison.<ref>{{cite web | title = Man convicted of Real IRA membership | author = | url = http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/0302/rira.html | publisher = ''[[RTÉ]]'' | date = 2 March 2004 | accessdate = 2007-03-14}}</ref>

In 2009, he appeared in [[Carrickmacross]] District Court for failing to produce insurance and driving without a licence at Tullyvaragh, Carrickmacross and also failing to produce insurance and a driving licence when stopped in Carrickmacross Court car park. He received a 12-month driving ban and a €3,250 fine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8094683.stm|title=Omagh bomb organiser's drive ban |date=2009-06-11|accessdate=2009-06-26|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>

== Background ==
He is a builder from Cullaville, County Monaghan.<ref>http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/omagh-bomb-legal-victory-the-men-behind-worst-atrocity-of-the-troubles-28486981.html</ref>

== Omagh bombing ==
{{main|Omagh bombing}}
In 2009, Daly, along with three other Real IRA members, were ruled to be civilly liable for the [[Omagh bombing]] and ordered by a Belfast court to pay £1.5 million to the victims of the attack. All four men refused.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/ira-militant-charged-29-omagh-bomb-murders-23277897 |title=Bail Denied for Real IRA Man Linked to Omagh Bomb |publisher=Associated Press |date=10 April 2014}}</ref>

On 10 April 2014, arising out of the police investigation into the Omagh bombing, Seamus Daly was charged with the murder of 29 people in Omagh in 1998, two charges linked to the explosion and two counts linked to an attempted explosion in [[Lisburn]] in April 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man charged with murdering 29 people in Omagh bombing|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0410/608132-omagh/|accessdate=11 April 2014|newspaper=RTÉ News|date=10 April 2014}}</ref> He appeared in court on 11 April and was remanded in custody due to the possibility he may flee the jurisdiction. On 6 May, Daly's case was adjourned for four weeks at the prosecutor's request.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-27300565 |title=Seamus Daly Omagh bomb case is adjourned |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2014}}</ref>

In February 2015 Northern Ireland's Director of Public Prosecutions ordered that Daly face charges "both for the Omagh bomb and [[1988 Lisburn van bombing|Lisburn bomb]] and the charges associated with those two incidents."<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/terrorism-in-the-uk/11417770/Omagh-bombing-trial-of-Real-IRA-suspect-Seamus-Daly-will-go-ahead.html|title = Omagh bombing: trial of Real IRA suspect Seamus Daly will go ahead|date = 17 February 2015|accessdate = |website = |publisher = The Telegraph|last = |first = }}</ref> After their star witness contradicted himself in pre-trial hearing, prosecutors in the North dropped all charges against Seamus Daly.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/02/world/europe/seamus-daly-omagh-bombing.html?_r=0|title = Britain Drops Case Against Last Suspect in 1998 Omagh Bombing|date = 1 March 2016|accessdate = |website = |publisher = The Irish Times|last = |first = }}</ref>

Daly was released from Maghaberry high-security prison in Co Antrim on 1 March 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.sky.com/story/1651229/omagh-seamus-daly-freed-as-charges-dropped|title = Omagh: Seamus Daly Freed As Charges Dropped|date = 1 March 2016|accessdate = |website = |publisher = Sky News|last = |first = }}</ref>

== Campaign for his release ==

Since his arrest in 2014, Daly's family and friends maintained his innocence. A committee was established in 2014 <ref>http://www.crossexaminer.co.uk/archives/14338</ref> to work on highlighting the case and they released a number of statements. A website and social media campaign <ref>https://www.facebook.com/releaseseamusdaly?ref=hl</ref> was established in July 2015 to highlight his ongoing imprisonment, which campaigners described as "the age old tactic of internment by remand."  
<ref>{{cite web |url=http://releaseseamusdaly.com/february-2015.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713221441/http://releaseseamusdaly.com/february-2015.html |archivedate=13 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

